## Summary

**Event Load: MEDIUM** — A light scheduled calendar against a loud, news-driven tape.

**The setup:** A textbook risk-on gap on the US-Iran peace deal. S&P futures +1.39%, Nasdaq 100 +2.22%, Russell +1.95%, VIX -5.83% to 16.65. The dislocation is energy — WTI -5.55% below $80, Brent -5.12% — on the prospect of a reopened Strait of Hormuz. Asia led (Nikkei +4.99%, Kospi +5.20%, SoftBank +10%); Europe followed except the oil-heavy FTSE.

**Why this Monday matters:** I cross-referenced the calendar file and flagged that today is the **Monday of a major convergence week** — FOMC Wed Jun 17 (Warsh's first meeting as Chair), Triple Witch + S&P rebalance Fri Jun 19, Russell reconstitution Jun 26. The witching-week playbook (long Monday open → exit Thursday close) aligns with the risk-on impulse, so I framed the bias as **tactically bullish but with elevated event risk** into a binary FOMC.

**Watchlist:** The mover list is almost entirely thesis names — a broad high-beta squeeze (MU +8.16%, OUST +9.17%, quantum/nuclear/storage all +5-7%). No watchlist earnings today. I noted technical divergences: FTNT overbought (RSI 69); CEG/LEU/SYM bouncing inside downtrends; AVGO up but still below its SMA20/50. Defense primes are flat-to-down — the de-escalation narrative cuts against them even in a rally.

**Honesty notes I preserved (no fabrication):**
- All 5 economic releases marked **Pending** (Actual = "—").
- The 2Y yield is flagged as a FRED prior-close value (FRED timed out).
- The Brent anomaly is explained as a real oil-crash move, not an error; the **GD = 360 anomaly** is flagged as unverified data — consistent with the known Schwab data-quality issues in your memory.
- SpaceX/SPCX treated as a confirmed IPO-debut story per the briefing's news analysis.

